Domain: Mine Safety Engineering using IoT-based smart gas monitoring.
Executive Summary: Underground coal mining involves serious safety risks due to the accumulation of hazardous gases such as methane and carbon monoxide, which can cause explosions and fatal accidents if not detected early. Existing gas monitoring methods are often manual and limited to specific locations, making continuous surveillance difficult in high-risk zones like goaf areas and return airways.
This project proposes an IoT-based smart gas monitoring system to continuously measure harmful gas concentrations at critical underground locations and transmit real-time data to a Central monitoring unit using mine-safe wireless communication. The system provides early warnings when gas levels approach unsafe limits, enabling timely safety actions and improved ventilation control.
By integrating continuous sensing and real-time monitoring, the proposed solution aims to enhance mine safety, reduce accident risks, and protect miners’ lives through proactive gas hazard management.
Objectives:
To develop an IoT-based smart gas monitoring system for early detection of hazardous gases and improvement of safety in underground coal mines:
•
Monitor Hazardous Gas Concentrations: Continuously measure methane, carbon monoxide, and other harmful gas levels in critical underground locations such as goaf edges, return airways, and electrical panels.
•
Early Warning and Risk Detection: Analyze real-time gas data to identify unsafe conditions and provide timely alerts before gas concentrations reach dangerous or explosive limits.
•
Support Mine Safety and Ventilation Management: Provide actionable information to assist mine operators in improving ventilation control, emergency response, and overall underground safety planning.
