Methodology:
1. Data Collection:
1. Collect real-time and historical data from fixed underground gas sensors measuring methane (CH₄), carbon monoxide (CO), oxygen (O₂), and carbon dioxide (CO₂) at critical mine locations such as goaf edges, return airways, and near electrical equipment.
2.
Gather mine-related operational and environmental data, including ventilation of airflow rates, mine layout, depth of workings, production activity, and geological conditions influencing gas release.
3.
Compile labeled datasets of mine safety conditions, such as normal atmosphere, warning-level gas concentration, and dangerous gas conditions, to support analysis and early warning generation.
2.Data Preprocessing:
•
Clean the collected data by handling missing sensor readings, removing abnormal values caused by sensor faults, and correcting inconsistent entries in gas concentration and ventilation data.
•
Normalize the data to a common scale (for example, 0–1) to ensure uniformity across different gas sensors such as methane, carbon monoxide, and oxygen
BIT SINDRI
sensors.
•
Synchronize time-series data from multiple underground sensors and mine operation records to enable accurate analysis of gas behavior over time
3.Feature Extraction:
1.Derive meaningful features from raw sensor data, such as:
i.
Gas concentration trends over time (moving averages, rate of increase or decrease of methane and carbon monoxide).
ii.
Relationships between gas concentration and ventilation parameters such as airflow velocity and direction.
iii.
Location-based features including sensor position (goaf edge, return airway, electrical zone) and distance from active working faces.
2. Apply feature reduction techniques such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to remove redundant features and improve the efficiency of gas prediction and safety analysis.
4.Model Training & Validation:
•
Select suitable machine learning algorithms such as Random Forest, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and Gradient Boosting to analyze underground gas sensor data collected through the IoT-based monitoring system.
•
Train the models using labeled gas concentration data to classify mine conditions into safe, warning, and dangerous levels, and to predict the risk of gas accumulation in advance.
•
Split the dataset into training (70%), validation (15%), and testing (15%) sets to ensure reliable model performance and unbiased evaluation.
•
Apply cross-validation techniques (k-fold validation) to improve model accuracy, reduce overfitting, and optimize hyperparameters for real-time gas monitoring applications.
